<i>-acum</i>. This is probably the chief source of the surname in Britain.","English: nickname for someone with gray hair or a gray beard, from Middle English <i>grey</i> (Old English <i>grǣg</i>, <i>grēg</i>) ‘gray’. In Ireland it has been used as a translation of various Gaelic surnames derived from <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled, gray’, including <b>Mac Giolla Riabhaigh</b>; see   McGreevy  . In North America, this surname has assimilated names with similar meaning from other languages.","French: habitational name from Gray in Haute-Saône or Le Gray in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Greiwe","meanings":["German: possibly a nickname from Middle High German <i>greibe</i> ‘sharp, tangy, dour’. Compare   Grey  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":6,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":16,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Grey was born about 1090, in Buckenham, Norfolk, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. John Grey."},"et":{"about 1090–Deceased":"umbes 1090–Surnud","1094–Female":"1094–Surnud","1108–1180":"1108–1180","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","about 1090":"umbes 1090","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1180":"1180","1108":"1108","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1090–Deceased":"noin 1090–Kuollut","1094–Female":"1094–Kuollut","1108–1180":"1108–1180","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","about 1090":"noin 1090","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1180":"1180","1108":"1108","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"about 1090–Deceased":"environ 1090–Décédé","1094–Female":"1094–Décédée","1108–1180":"1108–1180","1090–Male":"1090–Décédé","1106":"1106","1090":"1090","about 1090":"environ 1090","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1180":"1180","1108":"1108","Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Buckenham, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":